<br>
The people dying in the WTC bothered me no more then the people killed in a bus bombing in Israel.  The people dying in the WTC bothered me no more then the Marines that died in the Beirut bombing (actually I could relate to the Marines more then I could the accountants).  The fact that those people died doesn't disturb me any more then it did when Randy Weaver's wife was killed by federal agents.  Or when those people died in Columbine.  Or Waco.  Or the tens of thousands that Pol Pot, or Stalin, or Hitler, or Mussolini killed.  Or the girl in this news story.  Or the people of Kuwait.  Or the civilian people of Afghanistan, or the Sudan, or through the corrupt policies known as Apartheid.  Or the people in Bosnia, or the Native Americans at the hands of the settlers.  The people in North Korea, or Iraq, or in Oklahoma city.  Or Ted Bundy's victims for that matter.  <br>
<br>
I love my country and believe I served it with honor.  But to lament about the loss of American lives and ignore the other losses of life would make me in my psyche truly heartless.  So what do I do?  Do I sit and cry over the American lives lost, while by ignoring the losses of life in the rest of the world spit on the graves of anyone not American?  Or do I treat all of these lives equally important?  I choose to treat them all equally.<br>
<br>
So, how do I cope with all of the loss of life?  I can sit in the corner and cry about how unfair life is.  Or I can accept that death and cruelty are part of this world, and while I can help where I can, accept that this will happen.  To shed tears for those people who died untimely in this suicide attack and not miss a beat when an Israeli or a Palestine dies to me is unthinkable and inhuman.  It is not my call to judge the worth of another persons life.  I accept that death is the way of this world, and with that acceptance I feel no need to grieve over someone I do not know.  Remember, I feel that you cry for the living, not for the dead.  And since none of these people were part of my life, I have no reason to cry for what I would miss about them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uunfetered.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Unfetered</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Indifferent Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(1/17/02 9:48:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=194.topic&index=19>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ok, why do we care, and what is evil?</span><hr size=1> I understand now, I think.  Thanks for the answer. <p><p><TABLE STYLE=filter:GLOW(color="red",strength=#+9)><FONT COLOR="white">The Unfetered One, a lone crusader in a dangerous world...
